    <div align="left" id="post_message_501636"><div align="center" style="margin:5px; margin-top:5px; ">
<table width="85%" border="0" align="center" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" bgcolor="#333333" class="bbcodeQUOTE">
  
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/openq.gif" width="30" height="30" ></td>
    <td>
		<div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;">No one seems to care that oilriggers died, but god forbid flipper is inconvenienced.</div>
		</td>
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/closeq.gif" width="30" height="30" align="right"></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</div>In my case, I do care that the riggers died. Environmental disaster aside (for which I think the loss of stock, clean up costs, settlements, ect... is appropriate), a lot of people have died or been hurt in just a few short years, with everyone constantly harping on their safety record as being worse than anyone else's. (See the OSHA reports)<br />
<br />
This isn't me being angry about the environment, this is me being angry that it seems like BP pushes production as high and costs as low as they can, and it has a human cost that they're not being called to task for. Like they would be. If oil regulatory agencies weren't sniffing coke off their asses. Regularly ignoring safety and good drilling procedure, ignoring experts who are supposed to advise them, both increased the likelihood of people dying and of having an environmental catastrophe. <br />
<br />
I think some criminal charges would get the message across that that is unacceptable as &quot;just the cost of doing business.&quot; Saying it wasn't malicious doesn't excuse willful recklessness or a depraved indifference to the environmental and human cost, especially when it is turning them a profit to do so.</div>
